{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536208"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:04:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:04:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15713"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15713"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.02,0.08,0.84,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8404"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96809"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8404"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15713"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79424"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"675"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"2546"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4640"},{"type":"tags","id":"4705"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20246"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96809"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old Aboriginal man from a remote community in the Northern Territory presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of a non-itchy rash. He also reports fatigue, mild fever, and generalised aches. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as a bus driver. He reports unprotected sexual intercourse with more than one partner in the past six months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There is a copper-coloured maculopapular rash on his trunk and extremities, including his palms and soles. An image of this rash is shown below. There are several painless, enlarged lymph nodes in his neck and groin. Condylomata lata is noted around the anus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely pathogen causing this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Group A Streptococcus","Cytomegalovirus","Human immunodeficiency virus","Treponema pallidum","Neisseria gonorrhoeae"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of secondary syphilis, including a copper-coloured maculopapular rash involving palms and soles, generalised lymphadenopathy, condylomata lata, and constitutional symptoms. Secondary syphilis is the systemic stage of syphilis infection (caused by \u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E) occurring at the same time as or up to six months after resolution of the primary chancre. Patients with secondary syphilis are highly infectious.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/strong\u003E is a spirochete bacterium transmitted through sexual contact. After an initial chancre in primary syphilis (which may go unnoticed), the infection progresses to secondary syphilis with systemic manifestations as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGroup A Streptococcus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a rash although does not cause condylomata lata. It is not a sexually transmitted infection. It is an important pathogen to note, especially in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Island peoples, as acute rheumatic fever is a multi-system disease caused by an immunological response to Group A streptococcus infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytomegalovirus\u003C/strong\u003E infection can cause fever, fatigue, and lymphadenopathy but typically does not cause a widespread rash involving palms and soles. It can commonly present with prolonged fever and hepatosplenomegaly. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuman immunodeficiency virus\u003C/strong\u003E acute infection can present with fever, lymphadenopathy, and a rash, but the rash is typically more subtle and transient. While HIV testing should be performed in this patient, the presence of condylomata lata more likely suggests syphilis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes urethritis or cervicitis. While disseminated gonococcal infection can cause skin lesions, these are usually pustular or petechial, not the copper-colored maculopapular rash seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERemote Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities in Northern Australia have much higher notification rates of sexually transmitted infections. Syphilis is a nationally notifiable condition. It is imperative these cases are reported to the centre for disease control/local public health unit.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Syphilis is caused by Treponema pallidum, a spirochete bacterium.","Secondary syphilis typically presents with systemic symptoms including fatigue, fever, rash and lymphadenopathy.","Risk factors for syphilis include unprotected sexual intercourse with multiple partners."],"references":["Remote Primary Health Care Manuals. Tropical Health Orientation Manual. Alice Springs, NT: Centre for Remote Health; 2020"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79424"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15713"}},"stemMedia"